00:16.980 --> 00:20.980
us that there is exactly one way that cup was destined to break.

00:21.120 --> 00:22.620
One true outcome, yeah.

00:22.800 --> 00:28.120
Exactly. Like if you knew the exact angle it fell, the microscopic flaws in the ceramic,

00:28.120 --> 00:31.900
the exact humidity in the air, the precise molecular friction of your tile.

00:32.060 --> 00:34.080
Which is impossible to know, obviously.

00:34.280 --> 00:37.960
Right. Impossible for us. But the theory goes that if you could know it, you could calculate

00:37.960 --> 00:44.140
that exact, single, inevitable outcome. But we have a groundbreaking new AI model that

00:44.140 --> 00:47.240
suggests that standard view is, well, it's completely wrong.

00:47.340 --> 00:48.780
It really throws the whole thing out the window.

00:48.860 --> 00:54.780
It does. The universe doesn't have one true, hidden future. It has a multiverse of what

00:54.780 --> 01:00.780
this paper calls admissible continuations. And today, we are going to look at how artificial

01:00.780 --> 01:07.340
intelligence is basically abandoning traditional physics entirely to instead repair broken timelines.

01:07.340 --> 01:12.700
It's a complete inversion of how we think about predicting reality. And the source we're using

01:12.700 --> 01:17.220
for this deep dive is a highly theoretical paper from June, 2026.

01:17.380 --> 01:18.340
Right. By Flyxion.

01:18.340 --> 01:23.740
Yeah, by Flyxion. It's titled Repairing Futures, Admissible Continuation, Historical Reconstruction,

01:24.080 --> 01:29.700
and Diffusion-Based Physical Simulation. And what's fascinating here is that this paper proves

01:29.700 --> 01:34.440
that the way we've been trying to simulate the world, you know, step-by-step, calculating

01:34.440 --> 01:36.960
forces and mass, it's just a dead end.

01:37.040 --> 01:38.160
A total dead end.

01:38.220 --> 01:44.140
We are entering an era where AI treats the future not as a math equation to be solved,

01:44.140 --> 01:49.920
but as a damaged trajectory that needs to be basically mathematically forced back onto

01:49.920 --> 01:50.980
the tracks of reality.

01:50.980 --> 01:55.660
And what's wild is that this isn't just about making, like, better video game physics or

01:55.660 --> 02:01.020
cooler Hollywood CGI. This is a fundamental philosophical shift in how you, the listener,

02:01.380 --> 02:04.560
should view your own reality, your own memory, and your own future.

02:04.740 --> 02:06.120
It really is. It changes everything.

02:06.360 --> 02:10.480
But to understand how we get there, we kind of have to start by completely dismantling the

02:10.480 --> 02:14.120
foundation of classical mechanics. We have to kill something the paper calls the

02:14.120 --> 02:15.340
myth of the complete state.

02:15.340 --> 02:20.400
Right. So if you look at any traditional physics engine or simulation, and I mean,

02:20.480 --> 02:27.400
this goes back to the determinism of Laplace's demon centuries ago, the absolute bedrock assumption

02:27.400 --> 02:28.900
is that a system has a state.

02:29.000 --> 02:30.680
A frozen snapshot, basically.

02:30.900 --> 02:35.440
Exactly. The idea is that if you can take a frozen snapshot of the universe at exactly

02:35.440 --> 02:40.500
time t, and you capture every single relevant detail, you can use the laws of physics to

02:40.500 --> 02:43.740
perfectly calculate time t plus one, the next moment.

02:43.740 --> 02:48.560
It's a very comforting thought. You know, the universe as a giant predictable clockwork

02:48.560 --> 02:51.120
mechanism, you map the gears, you know the time.

02:51.220 --> 02:55.120
It is comforting, but it is mathematically and physically an illusion.

02:55.460 --> 02:55.860
Wow.

02:56.020 --> 03:00.280
In classical mechanics, this is called a Markovian assumption. That's the idea that the next

03:00.280 --> 03:03.780
state only depends on the current state and not on the history of how it got there.

03:04.100 --> 03:09.260
But to have a complete state for even a really mundane system, you need an impossible amount

03:09.260 --> 03:09.780
of information.

