18:05.660 --> 18:11.040
So it physically bends the corrupted timeline until it snaps onto the train tracks of reality.

18:11.180 --> 18:15.940
Exactly. It repairs the impossible physics. And this is where we have to look under the hood at how

18:15.940 --> 18:19.500
it does this, which involves the attention mechanism of the transformer architecture.

18:19.500 --> 18:20.480
Okay. The transformer.

18:20.480 --> 18:25.200
You mentioned earlier the problem of the autoregressive models melting because they forget the shape of

18:25.200 --> 18:31.060
the object. Fisiformer doesn't melt because it uses self-attention across the temporal dimension.

18:31.280 --> 18:36.380
Okay. Stop there. What does self-attention across the temporal dimension actually look like in

18:36.380 --> 18:40.060
practice? Walk me through what the AI is, you know, looking at.

18:40.060 --> 18:45.180
Let's visualize the timeline of our bouncing block as a strip of film, maybe a hundred frames long.

18:45.640 --> 18:51.260
In a traditional step-by-step model, the AI looks at frame five, uses it to draw frame six,

18:51.660 --> 18:54.240
looks at frame six, uses it to draw frame seven.

18:54.340 --> 18:55.280
He's wearing blinders.

18:55.480 --> 19:00.080
Right. But Fisiformer's attention mechanism looks at the entire strip of film simultaneously.

19:00.580 --> 19:06.100
It creates a mathematical query. Let's say a specific corner of the wooden block in frame 45 is

19:06.100 --> 19:10.760
slightly out of place. It has drifted due to noise, causing the block to look stretched.

19:10.900 --> 19:11.680
Because it's corrupted.

19:11.980 --> 19:16.320
Yes. The attention head in frame 45 basically shouts out to the rest of the timeline,

19:16.720 --> 19:20.520
hey, what is the exact distance I am supposed to be from the center of the block?

19:20.580 --> 19:21.640
And the other frame's answer.

19:21.640 --> 19:27.660
Yes. Frame five, which is closer to the clean starting conditions, holds the key to that query.

19:28.520 --> 19:34.540
The attention mechanism compares the stretch distance in frame 45 to the rigid distance established in frame five.

19:34.640 --> 19:35.480
Oh, that's brilliant.

19:35.480 --> 19:40.580
It mathematically recognizes the discrepancy that the violation of historical coherence,

19:40.820 --> 19:45.560
and it applies a repair vector to frame 45, pulling that corner back into place.

19:45.560 --> 19:50.880
It does this for thousands of points across hundreds of frames, millions of times a second.

19:51.500 --> 19:55.260
The future constrains the past. The beginning constrains the end.

19:55.780 --> 20:02.000
The whole timeline iteratively tightens itself until the object is perfectly rigid across all 100 frames.

20:02.000 --> 20:10.380
That is absolutely mind-bending. The future reaching back to constrain the past inside the simulation to ensure the object remains coherent.

20:10.620 --> 20:12.500
It's a completely new way of handling time.

20:12.700 --> 20:17.520
And the paper formalizes this whole repair cycle into something called the sphere pop formulation.

20:17.520 --> 20:22.400
This was a completely new term for me. Can you break down the steps of a sphere pop?

20:22.620 --> 20:26.260
The sphere pop formulation is the mathematical heartbeat of this repair process.

20:26.680 --> 20:28.940
It breaks down into four sequential operations.

20:29.260 --> 20:30.500
First, you pop a witness.

20:31.000 --> 20:35.620
We need to define witness here. It sounds like a legal term, but here it means the initial conditions.

20:35.620 --> 20:44.840
Correct. The witness is, whatever partial information you have at time zero, the starting position, the initial velocity, maybe a boundary of the room, you pop that from the environment.

20:45.080 --> 20:46.980
Step two, you expand the set.

20:47.180 --> 20:48.840
This is where we create the chaos.

20:49.180 --> 20:59.200
Yes. The AI takes that witness and artificially inflates it with massive amounts of noise, generating a wild, corrupted, entirely impossible history.

20:59.440 --> 21:02.060
It throws it out into the chaotic ambient space.

21:02.460 --> 21:03.520
Which feels wrong.

21:03.520 --> 21:08.360
It seems counterproductive, but it's necessary to explore all the mathematical possibilities.

21:09.300 --> 21:13.340
Step three, you refuse inadmissible histories via repair.

21:13.540 --> 21:16.380
This is the diffusion attention mechanism we just talked about.

21:16.460 --> 21:19.240
Exactly. The AI enters the denoising loop.

21:19.700 --> 21:29.100
It looks at the massive, noisy set of possibilities and iteratively pushes it closer and closer to the physical manifold, rejecting the parts of the timeline that violate rigidity or gravity.

21:29.220 --> 21:30.740
It repairs the impossible physics.

21:30.880 --> 21:31.260
It does.

21:31.260 --> 21:34.960
Finally, step four, you collapse the repaired history.

21:35.160 --> 21:36.400
Snap it onto the train tracks.

21:36.520 --> 21:37.760
The timeline reaches the manifold.

21:38.280 --> 21:41.140
It is now physically admissible, coherent, and stable.

21:41.520 --> 21:44.740
That single point on the manifold is your final generated trajectory.

21:45.220 --> 21:52.820
What you perceive as the AI generating a simulation is actually just the byproduct of this relentless repair process collapsing back onto reality.

21:52.820 --> 22:03.000
I want to go back to that word witness, because section five of the paper takes this concept and turns it into a profound philosophical statement about how we perceive time.

22:03.240 --> 22:05.000
It really challenges our assumptions.

22:05.380 --> 22:05.580
Yeah.

22:05.700 --> 22:10.380
The paper explicitly states that initial conditions the witness do not store the future.

22:10.540 --> 22:11.080
They do not.

22:11.080 --> 22:14.540
And this is another sharp break from classical mechanics.

22:14.540 --> 22:26.560
In a Newtonian world, the initial conditions, like the exact position, mass, and velocity of a set of billiard balls, contain the entire future of the billiard table within them.

22:26.920 --> 22:28.840
The future is pre-encoded in the present.

22:29.020 --> 22:29.300
Right.

22:29.540 --> 22:31.460
You just need to run the math to decode it.

22:31.460 --> 22:50.240
I was trying to think of how to visualize this, and I keep coming back to a literal crime scene witness.

22:50.360 --> 22:50.840
Let's hear it.

22:50.840 --> 22:54.500
Imagine a detective is trying to reconstruct a timeline of a robbery.

22:55.120 --> 23:01.200
A witness steps forward and says, I saw a red sedan speeding away facing north at 9.0 p.m.

23:01.460 --> 23:06.400
Now, that witness does not know exactly what happened in the entire city that day.

23:06.820 --> 23:08.720
They don't have the complete state of the crime.

23:09.240 --> 23:12.300
The future path of that red sedan is not stored in their brain.

23:12.480 --> 23:13.120
No, it isn't.

23:13.200 --> 23:19.180
But what their testimony does is give the detective just enough constraints to dramatically narrow down the suspects.

23:19.180 --> 23:21.760
It eliminates any car that went south.

23:22.100 --> 23:23.820
It eliminates any blue cars.

23:24.060 --> 23:25.060
It filters out the noise.

23:25.220 --> 23:25.340
Right.

23:25.500 --> 23:27.080
The witness doesn't contain the truth.

23:27.360 --> 23:31.020
The witness just narrows down the admissible continuations of the timeline.

23:31.560 --> 23:33.420
That analogy cracks perfectly with the mathematics.

23:34.140 --> 23:37.020
The witness provides the boundary conditions for the repair operator.

23:37.680 --> 23:43.880
And to quantify exactly how helpful a witness is, the paper introduces a metric called continuation entropy.

23:44.560 --> 23:47.300
Now, entropy usually means disorder or chaos.

23:47.520 --> 23:48.360
How does it apply here?

23:48.360 --> 23:52.780
Here, it refers to the logarithmic volume of the admissible continuation set.

23:52.840 --> 23:54.100
Let's break that down without the jargon.

23:54.240 --> 23:59.700
It basically asks, given what the witness saw, how many possible futures are still open?

24:00.260 --> 24:02.060
How wide is the pie of possibility?

24:02.560 --> 24:06.620
So, if the situation is highly constrained and predictable, the entropy is low.

24:06.940 --> 24:07.220
Yes.

24:07.900 --> 24:11.780
The paper uses the example of simple, free-flight scenes.

24:12.760 --> 24:14.620
Imagine you toss a baseball through the air.

24:14.620 --> 24:20.360
Once it leaves your hand, assuming we know its basic starting velocity and we know Earth's gravity,

24:20.500 --> 24:26.060
there are very few unobserved parameters that can drastically alter its path before it hits the ground.

24:26.180 --> 24:27.420
It's pretty much a set path.

24:27.580 --> 24:31.480
The wind might shift at a millimeter, but overall, its trajectory is locked.

24:31.480 --> 24:33.980
The continuation entropy is very low.

24:34.440 --> 24:36.700
The volume of possible futures is tiny.

24:37.040 --> 24:38.320
But what if it's a chaotic scene?

24:38.900 --> 24:42.880
Like, what if I take a handful of jagged dice, bouncy balls, and glass marbles,

24:43.000 --> 24:46.840
and I throw them all as hard as I can against an uneven, rocky cave wall?

24:47.000 --> 24:49.020
Then your continuation entropy is massive.

24:49.580 --> 24:51.280
The outcomes are wildly diverse.

24:51.280 --> 24:55.940
A microscopic difference in the contact angle when a bouncy ball hits a rock face

24:55.940 --> 24:58.480
can produce a completely divergent trajectory.

24:58.640 --> 24:59.200
It could go anywhere.

24:59.420 --> 25:00.180
It could bounce left.

25:00.280 --> 25:01.040
It could bounce right.

25:01.120 --> 25:02.520
It could hit a die and scatter.

25:03.620 --> 25:06.820
In this scenario, your initial conditions, the velocity of your throw,

25:06.940 --> 25:09.500
leave a massive number of physically admissible futures open.

25:10.020 --> 25:11.480
The logarithmic volume is huge.

25:11.740 --> 25:13.000
Which kind of begs the question,

25:13.860 --> 25:17.280
if the entropy is massive, how do we trust the AI?

25:17.960 --> 25:19.820
That's a huge problem in the field.

25:19.820 --> 25:23.420
Right. If we ask Fisiformer to simulate that handful of dice,

25:23.700 --> 25:27.440
and it gives us one beautiful, realistic animation of them bouncing,

25:28.260 --> 25:30.980
how do we know if it actually predicted a likely outcome,

25:31.300 --> 25:34.640
or if it just randomly guessed one out of a billion possibilities?

25:35.440 --> 25:36.640
How do we measure its confidence?

25:37.160 --> 25:38.840
We can't use traditional metrics.

25:39.020 --> 25:43.400
Usually, AI engineers use mean squared error, MSE.

25:43.920 --> 25:47.760
They take the AI's prediction, compare it to a real-world video of the event,

25:47.760 --> 25:49.500
and measure the distance between the two.

25:49.820 --> 25:50.200
Makes sense.

25:50.380 --> 25:54.180
But Flyxion points out that MSE is terrible for high-entropy physical systems.

25:54.980 --> 25:57.640
If the AI perfectly predicts a physically valid bounce,

25:57.980 --> 26:01.960
but it bounces left instead of right because of a microscopic variation in the rock,

26:02.480 --> 26:04.780
MSE will say the AI failed completely.

26:04.920 --> 26:06.820
Because it didn't match the exact video.

26:06.940 --> 26:09.280
Right. It penalizes valid alternative futures.

26:09.280 --> 26:11.360
So we need a new ruler entirely.

26:11.740 --> 26:12.080
Exactly.

26:12.600 --> 26:16.160
Flyxion introduces a formal measure called the witness adequacy functional,

26:16.720 --> 26:18.260
represented by the Greek letter lambda.

26:19.200 --> 26:21.840
Instead of measuring against one true ground reality,

26:22.380 --> 26:25.680
lambda measures the geometry of the possibility space itself.

26:25.920 --> 26:26.200
Okay.

26:26.360 --> 26:29.840
It measures the worst-case distance between any admissible continuation

26:29.840 --> 26:33.120
and the specific future the model generated.

26:33.320 --> 26:36.060
Walk me through what lambda looks like in practice.

26:36.060 --> 26:37.520
Like, what do the numbers mean?

26:37.980 --> 26:41.580
If lambda is small, it means the witness tightly constrained the future.

26:41.940 --> 26:46.620
It means that all the possible physical realities look very similar to the one the AI generated.

26:46.700 --> 26:47.700
You can trust the prediction.

26:47.860 --> 26:48.520
Like the baseball.

26:48.720 --> 26:49.060
Exactly.

26:49.600 --> 26:52.880
But if lambda is large, like in your Dyson bouncy ball example,

26:53.120 --> 26:57.140
it tells the engineer, listen, the AI's prediction is perfectly physically valid,

26:57.140 --> 27:02.980
but the witness left so many doors open that this prediction is just one tiny narrow slice

27:02.980 --> 27:04.900
of a massive pie of possibility.

27:05.420 --> 27:07.480
Okay. So it's a confidence score, but for physics.

27:07.780 --> 27:11.960
Right. It gives us a geometric mathematically sound way to measure physical confidence

27:11.960 --> 27:14.900
without relying on the illusion of a single true outcome.

27:15.140 --> 27:17.160
Okay. This all sounds incredibly sophisticated.

27:17.640 --> 27:21.320
The model evaluates the witness, maps the continuation entropy,

27:21.320 --> 27:27.260
and iteratively repairs a corrupted timeline across hundreds of frames using temporal attention

27:27.260 --> 27:29.580
until it snaps onto the physical manifold.

27:29.960 --> 27:30.920
That's a lot of math.

27:31.100 --> 27:35.900
It is. And if I am listening to this, I am thinking, this AI is a genius.

27:36.380 --> 27:39.660
It deeply, fundamentally understands the laws of physics.

27:39.740 --> 27:39.920
Wow.

27:39.920 --> 27:42.960
But then the paper drops an absolute bombshell.

27:43.160 --> 27:44.780
It asks a blunt question.

27:45.520 --> 27:48.520
Does this model actually understand the laws of physics?

27:48.720 --> 27:52.000
And the answer is a resounding categorical no.

27:52.160 --> 27:53.700
It does not understand physics at all.

27:54.120 --> 27:57.980
To understand why, the paper makes a vital, uncompromising distinction

27:57.980 --> 28:02.060
between two concepts that we often blur together, kinematics and mechanics.

28:02.220 --> 28:02.500
Okay.

28:02.700 --> 28:07.100
What physical former and similar diffusion models learn are admissible kinematics, not mechanics.

28:07.180 --> 28:09.500
Okay. You need to draw a hard line between those two for us.

28:09.500 --> 28:10.280
What is the difference?

28:10.560 --> 28:12.600
Mechanics is the causal engine of the universe.

28:12.940 --> 28:14.620
It explains why a trajectory occurs.

28:14.800 --> 28:20.540
It involves forces, mass, inertia, gravity, Newton's laws of motion, the conservation of energy.

28:20.640 --> 28:22.120
The actual invisible rules.

28:22.520 --> 28:22.800
Right.

28:23.200 --> 28:28.680
If you understand mechanics, you understand the underlying invisible rules that govern matter.

28:29.700 --> 28:34.660
Kinematics, on the other hand, merely describes which trajectories occur.

28:34.940 --> 28:35.820
Just the results.

28:35.820 --> 28:37.520
It is the geometry of motion.

28:37.520 --> 28:42.780
It is the shape of the path an object takes, completely devoid of any understanding of the

28:42.780 --> 28:44.580
forces that pushed it along that path.

28:44.680 --> 28:49.900
So it's the difference between knowing how an engine works versus just watching a car drive

28:49.900 --> 28:52.100
by and memorizing the shape of the road it took.

28:52.240 --> 28:52.640
Exactly.

28:53.020 --> 28:53.920
Think of Plato's cave.

28:54.600 --> 28:58.760
The AI is chained in the cave, watching the shadows of physics dance on the wall.

28:59.000 --> 29:01.040
It watches millions of hours of training data.

29:01.100 --> 29:01.440
Right.

29:01.440 --> 29:05.880
It sees two solid blocks of wood approach each other, and it sees them bounce apart.

29:06.240 --> 29:09.940
It learns that blocks don't pass through each other, but it doesn't know why.

29:10.160 --> 29:11.120
It just knows they don't.

29:11.200 --> 29:16.740
It has no concept of electrostatic repulsion between atoms or the concept of solid mass.

29:16.880 --> 29:21.380
It only knows they don't pass through each other because, in all its training data, it

29:21.380 --> 29:25.100
never saw the geometric shape of two boxes clipping through each other.

29:25.100 --> 29:31.420
So it learned the visual shadow that physics casts without ever understanding the object

29:31.420 --> 29:32.340
casting the shadow.

29:33.040 --> 29:36.180
The learned distribution is just empirical kinematics.

29:36.460 --> 29:36.720
Yes.

29:37.320 --> 29:38.920
It is a coordinate shadow model.

29:39.100 --> 29:40.620
Okay, I'm going to play devil's advocate here.

29:41.100 --> 29:44.740
Imagine I'm a video game designer or even an engineer running basic simulations.

29:45.220 --> 29:50.720
If the AI can predict a bouncing block of wood and the visual shadow looks perfectly real

29:50.720 --> 29:56.440
and it never actually violates the rules of reality on screen, does it actually matter

29:56.440 --> 29:57.980
that it's faking the why?

29:58.620 --> 29:59.600
That's a fair question.

29:59.780 --> 30:05.120
If the result is indistinguishable from reality, why do we care if it understands underlying mechanics?

30:05.260 --> 30:06.120
We care deeply.

30:06.900 --> 30:12.040
And the paper explains why, in a section on failure modes as admissibility boundary detection,

30:12.540 --> 30:15.180
the illusion works perfectly until it doesn't.

30:15.300 --> 30:16.040
Where does it break down?

30:16.560 --> 30:18.940
When the AI fails, it doesn't fail gracefully.

30:18.940 --> 30:21.640
It fails precisely at the boundaries of contact.

30:22.140 --> 30:27.240
It hallucinates spurious contacts where objects react before touching, or it allows two objects

30:27.240 --> 30:29.580
to slightly clip through each other for a frame or two.

30:29.660 --> 30:31.620
Why does it fail exactly when they touch?

30:31.940 --> 30:38.200
Because a contact manifold, the exact mathematical moment two rigid objects collide, is a highly

30:38.200 --> 30:41.080
singular mathematically sharp geometric structure.

30:41.820 --> 30:45.260
The rules of motion change discontinuously in a single millisecond.

30:45.840 --> 30:47.420
The smooth geometry shatters.

30:47.420 --> 30:49.780
It gets complicated really fast.

30:50.000 --> 30:50.140
Right.

30:50.620 --> 30:56.220
Because the AI is only looking at the smooth, kinematic shape of motion, it lacks the resolution

30:56.220 --> 30:57.900
to handle that sharp boundary.

30:58.440 --> 31:03.440
When the shadow gets confusing and jagged, it messes up, because it doesn't have the underlying

31:03.440 --> 31:04.840
mechanics to fall back on.

31:04.960 --> 31:06.360
It can't reason its way out.

31:06.360 --> 31:11.840
But no, it can't pause and calculate, wait, object A has 10 kilograms of mass and is moving

31:11.840 --> 31:12.900
at 5 meters per second.

31:13.360 --> 31:15.780
Therefore, the transfer of kinetic energy must be X.

31:16.180 --> 31:17.820
It just guesses the shape of the balance.

31:17.960 --> 31:21.000
Ah, and it also destroys counterfactual reasoning, right?

31:21.140 --> 31:25.780
Like, if it only knows the shadows that is memorized, you can't ask it, what would happen

31:25.780 --> 31:28.500
if I suddenly doubled the gravity halfway through the balance?

31:28.500 --> 31:28.980
Exactly.

31:29.480 --> 31:32.980
It has never seen the shadow of double gravity, so it has no idea how to generate it.

31:33.340 --> 31:35.720
It cannot extrapolate outside its training distribution.

31:36.100 --> 31:37.220
So how do we fix this?

31:37.340 --> 31:41.540
Does the paper offer a way to give the AI actual mechanical understanding?

31:41.960 --> 31:42.580
It does.

31:42.660 --> 31:48.660
In a highly theoretical proposal called the RSVP Theoretic Extension, Flyxion argues that

31:48.660 --> 31:54.120
to achieve true counterfactual reasoning, we have to move beyond just tracking the coordinates

31:54.120 --> 31:54.760
of objects.

31:55.140 --> 32:00.200
We have to teach the AI to learn the underlying causal fields that govern this space.

32:00.460 --> 32:02.660
Okay, what does RSVP stand for?

32:03.240 --> 32:05.820
RSVP stands for the components of this new model.

32:06.300 --> 32:11.020
The core components are a scalar capacity field, a vector transport field, and a constraint

32:11.020 --> 32:11.500
density.

32:11.760 --> 32:13.400
Okay, those are really dense terms.

32:13.580 --> 32:16.080
We cannot let those slide without translating them for the listener.

32:16.200 --> 32:17.140
Let's take them one by one.

32:17.140 --> 32:22.020
If I'm simulating our bouncing block of wood, what is the scalar capacity field?

32:22.420 --> 32:26.240
Think of the scalar capacity field as the invisible potential for interaction in the

32:26.240 --> 32:27.400
space around the object.

32:28.140 --> 32:32.940
It's a field of number scalars that represents how full or empty the space is and how capable

32:32.940 --> 32:35.100
it is of absorbing or resisting force.

32:35.240 --> 32:36.800
So it's basically mapping the environment.

32:37.180 --> 32:43.320
It tells the AI, this region of space is occupied by a dense material and this region is empty air.

32:43.320 --> 32:48.740
Okay, so it gives the AI a sense of density and presence rather than just empty geometric

32:48.740 --> 32:49.340
coordinates.

32:50.120 --> 32:52.080
What about the vector transport field?

32:52.520 --> 32:55.660
The vector transport field is the invisible highway of momentum.

32:56.620 --> 32:58.480
Vectors have direction and magnitude.

32:59.420 --> 33:03.020
When the block of wood hits the floor, the energy doesn't just disappear.

33:03.520 --> 33:04.280
It has to travel.

33:04.540 --> 33:05.740
Energy has to go somewhere.

33:05.740 --> 33:11.420
The vector transport field maps exactly how kinetic energy, momentum, and forces move through

33:11.420 --> 33:12.920
the space and through the objects.

33:13.440 --> 33:16.000
It teaches the AI the flow of causality.

33:16.260 --> 33:20.660
So instead of just seeing the block magically bounce, it sees the actual invisible wave of

33:20.660 --> 33:23.260
energy hit the floor and push the block back up.

33:23.340 --> 33:25.460
And the third one, constraint density.

33:25.460 --> 33:29.720
Constraint density maps how sharply the physical rules apply in a given region.

33:30.240 --> 33:34.760
In open air, the constraint density is low, the block can move freely, but exactly at the

33:34.760 --> 33:38.360
boundary of the solid floor, the constraint density spikes to infinity.

33:38.580 --> 33:39.300
It creates a wall.

33:39.620 --> 33:42.640
It creates a mathematical wall that absolutely forbids penetration.

33:43.020 --> 33:43.740
This is incredible.

33:44.220 --> 33:49.420
If you teach the AI these three fields, capacity, transport, and constraints, you elevate it.

33:49.700 --> 33:50.040
Yes.

33:50.040 --> 33:56.020
You shift the model from being a mere coordinate shadow model to a true field world model.

33:56.660 --> 34:00.460
The physical geometry of the bounce isn't just memorized from training data anymore.

34:00.980 --> 34:04.120
It emerges naturally from the interaction of these causal fields.

34:04.380 --> 34:08.440
It bridges the gap between kinematics and true mechanics.

34:08.740 --> 34:13.440
But until we fully realize that field world model, we are stuck with diffusion models that

34:13.440 --> 34:18.600
occasionally fail at contact boundaries, which brings us to the very practical problem

34:18.600 --> 34:19.700
of how we train them.

34:19.700 --> 34:25.480
If the model fails at sharp physical boundaries, the paper argues we are currently training

34:25.480 --> 34:26.640
them entirely wrong.

34:27.020 --> 34:29.120
We have to stop using Gaussian noise.

34:29.260 --> 34:29.500
Right.

34:29.860 --> 34:32.300
Let's review how standard diffusion models are trained.

34:32.980 --> 34:37.080
You take a clean piece of data, like an image of a dog, and you add Gaussian noise.

34:37.440 --> 34:41.640
You basically sprinkle random television static over the pixels, corrupting the coordinate

34:41.640 --> 34:44.620
space, and you force the AI to reverse the process.

34:44.740 --> 34:45.720
Which works for images.

34:45.720 --> 34:51.500
But Flyxion points out that theorem 7.2 proves this is fundamentally the wrong approach for

34:51.500 --> 34:52.700
physics trajectories.

34:52.700 --> 34:54.920
Why, I mean, static is static, right?

34:55.020 --> 34:58.260
If you want to teach it to repair a timeline, shouldn't you scramble the timeline?

34:58.480 --> 35:03.580
Because Gaussian noise doesn't correspond to any physically meaningful inadmissibility.

35:04.320 --> 35:09.620
In the real world, physics doesn't fail by suddenly turning into random localized static.

35:09.980 --> 35:10.760
That's true.

35:10.760 --> 35:15.380
A wooden block doesn't just have one corner dissolve into a cloud of random coordinates

35:15.380 --> 35:16.980
while the rest stays solid.

35:17.580 --> 35:23.300
If you train the AI to fix static, you are just teaching it advanced image smoothing.

35:23.680 --> 35:26.100
You aren't teaching it the structural rules of reality.

35:26.420 --> 35:27.740
Okay, I have an analogy for this.

35:27.860 --> 35:33.020
Let's say you, the listener, are tasked with training a master mechanic to fix car engines.

35:33.240 --> 35:33.920
Oh, that's good.

35:33.920 --> 35:39.420
The old way, the Gaussian noise way, is taking a hammer, randomly smashing the engine block

35:39.420 --> 35:42.180
into tiny pieces of shrapnel and saying, fix it.

35:42.340 --> 35:43.920
Right, which teaches them nothing.

35:44.040 --> 35:44.460
Exactly.

35:44.800 --> 35:49.060
That doesn't teach the mechanic how a carburetor works or how the timing don't function.

35:49.180 --> 35:50.420
It's just random destruction.

35:50.700 --> 35:51.680
It's an excellent analogy.

35:51.820 --> 35:53.000
So what is the alternative?

35:53.840 --> 35:56.820
Flyxion introduces admissibility structured perturbations.

35:56.820 --> 36:03.760
If we want the AI to learn how to repair broken physics, we must train it by violating specific

36:03.760 --> 36:04.800
physical constraints.

36:05.280 --> 36:08.640
We have to break the simulation in ways that make mathematical sense.

36:08.840 --> 36:13.880
So going back to our mechanic, instead of smashing the engine with a hammer, you intentionally

36:13.880 --> 36:16.280
loosen a specific serpentine belt.

36:16.820 --> 36:20.180
You subtly misalign the timing gears by two degrees.

36:20.520 --> 36:23.040
You drain exactly half the brake fluid.

36:23.100 --> 36:23.980
You give them real problems.

36:23.980 --> 36:28.920
You break the structure of the machine, so the mechanic has to learn the specific structural

36:28.920 --> 36:32.840
repair operators to bring it back to a working state.

36:33.360 --> 36:33.920
Precisely.

36:33.920 --> 36:39.860
In the context of the AI, instead of adding static to the simulation of a rigid block, the

36:39.860 --> 36:45.760
training process artificially bends the mathematical coordinates so the rigid block acts elastic.

36:46.460 --> 36:51.500
Or it introduces a mathematical drift to the velocity vectors so that momentum is suddenly

36:51.500 --> 36:53.160
not conserved across frames.

36:53.160 --> 36:54.280
Or it skips time.

36:54.380 --> 36:54.580
Right.

36:54.660 --> 36:58.500
It introduces random temporal gaps, deleting frames 10 through 15 entirely.

36:58.620 --> 37:02.980
And then you force the AI to look at that bent block or that broken momentum and say,

37:03.100 --> 37:05.860
repair this specific physical violation.

37:06.020 --> 37:06.320
Yes.

37:07.200 --> 37:09.980
This is the essence of the repair equivalence theorem.

37:10.640 --> 37:13.240
Gaussian diffusion repairs coordinate space corruption.

37:13.920 --> 37:18.120
Admissibility structured diffusion repairs specific physical constraint violations.

37:18.420 --> 37:19.980
It's learning the grammar of physics.

37:19.980 --> 37:20.640
Exactly.

37:21.080 --> 37:27.340
If you want the neural network's internal inductive logic to align with physical reality, you

37:27.340 --> 37:29.440
have to perturb it using physical rules.

37:29.700 --> 37:34.900
You have to teach it the grammar of physics by making it correct grammatical errors in motion.

37:35.080 --> 37:37.140
We have been talking a lot about motion.

37:37.400 --> 37:40.300
Histories, trajectories, boundaries, blocks of wood.

37:40.300 --> 37:46.440
But the paper takes a hard left turn here into deep philosophy because we haven't actually

37:46.440 --> 37:49.740
asked what the things moving along these trajectories actually are.

37:50.080 --> 37:51.400
This is where it gets really interesting.

37:51.680 --> 37:52.400
What is an object?

37:53.120 --> 37:56.400
Section 8 is titled Objecthood as Emergent Coherence.

37:56.940 --> 38:00.600
And it makes a claim that frankly forced me to put the paper down and stare at the wall

38:00.600 --> 38:01.040
for a minute.

38:01.600 --> 38:04.620
It asserts that objects do not exist as primitive entities.

38:04.620 --> 38:07.460
It is the most conceptually radical part of the paper.

38:08.120 --> 38:10.060
Human perception is incredibly biased.

38:10.380 --> 38:11.980
When you look around your room, you see things.

38:12.060 --> 38:13.920
You see a chair, a coffee cup, a laptop.

38:14.080 --> 38:14.560
Or objects.

38:14.820 --> 38:19.100
You assume these objects are fundamental, primitive building blocks of reality.

38:19.240 --> 38:20.800
They exist first and then they move.

38:21.640 --> 38:27.880
But Flyxion argues, via Proposition 8.2, Historical Coherence, that objecthood is not a property

38:27.880 --> 38:28.500
of a thing.

38:28.700 --> 38:29.860
It is an emergent pattern.

38:30.220 --> 38:32.100
It is a relational property of a history.

38:32.260 --> 38:33.900
Okay, you're going to have to translate that formula.

38:33.900 --> 38:36.300
Let's take a rigid body, like the chair.

38:36.860 --> 38:39.180
If the chair isn't a thing, what is it?

38:39.800 --> 38:42.520
Mathematically, to the AI, what is a rigid chair?

38:42.880 --> 38:45.520
It is not an entity with a labeled chair attached to it.

38:45.640 --> 38:49.000
It is simply a cluster of points, vertices, and space.

38:49.080 --> 38:50.260
Just a cloud of points.

38:50.340 --> 38:55.000
If you track those points over time and you observe that point A maintains the exact same

38:55.000 --> 38:59.760
distance from point B and point B maintains the exact same distance from point C, regardless

38:59.760 --> 39:01.120
of how the whole cluster moves.

39:01.120 --> 39:05.900
That unbroken mathematical relationship is called historical coherence.

39:05.900 --> 39:07.640
So the AI doesn't see a chair?

39:07.800 --> 39:08.020
No.

39:08.400 --> 39:11.240
It sees a historically coherent trajectory of points.

39:11.480 --> 39:12.880
The coherence is the object.

39:13.640 --> 39:17.000
The objecthood is constituted by the rigidity of its trajectory.

39:17.520 --> 39:22.080
So the paper is saying the object doesn't exist first and then decide to obey rigidity.

39:22.080 --> 39:27.820
The mathematical pattern of rigidity exists, and our human brains slap a label on that persistent

39:27.820 --> 39:29.320
pattern and call it an object.

39:29.540 --> 39:30.020
Exactly.

39:30.800 --> 39:33.460
Objecthood is an emergent property of admissibility.

39:33.960 --> 39:36.400
And this isn't just philosophical navel-gazing.

39:37.020 --> 39:43.380
This fundamental shift explains one of the most astonishing empirical real-world results of

39:43.380 --> 39:44.540
the physiformer model.

39:44.660 --> 39:44.940
Right.

39:45.360 --> 39:47.260
The training data versus the test data.

39:47.400 --> 39:48.640
Tell them about the Stanford bunny.

39:48.640 --> 39:53.680
When the researchers trained physiformer, they wanted to test its ability to generalize.

39:54.180 --> 39:58.780
So they restricted its training data purely to simple, convex, geometric primitives.

39:59.040 --> 40:01.580
Cubes, basic blocks, cylinders.

40:01.740 --> 40:02.720
Really simple stuff.

40:02.800 --> 40:06.260
The most complex object it ever saw during its training had 88 vertices.

40:06.500 --> 40:07.740
It was never shown anything complex.

40:08.100 --> 40:10.080
But after training was complete, they gave it a test.

40:10.080 --> 40:15.220
They asked it to simulate the physics of a highly complex 3D mesh of a fish, a detailed

40:15.220 --> 40:19.740
teapot, and the Stanford bunny, a famous 3D test model that has hundreds and hundreds

40:19.740 --> 40:20.280
of vertices.

40:20.800 --> 40:26.740
Now, if you take a standard visual AI, an AI trained to recognize images of cubes, and

40:26.740 --> 40:29.380
you show it a picture of a bunny, it fails completely.

40:30.040 --> 40:32.440
It says, I don't know what that is, that's not a cube.

40:32.440 --> 40:34.640
But physiformer succeeded flawlessly.

40:35.500 --> 40:40.540
It simulated the bunny bouncing, tumbling, and colliding perfectly without a single moment

40:40.540 --> 40:41.200
of retraining.

40:41.340 --> 40:41.980
Wait, really?

40:42.120 --> 40:43.020
How is that possible?

40:43.240 --> 40:48.100
How does an AI trained on 88-point cubes know how to animate a 500-point bunny?

40:48.360 --> 40:52.640
Because, returning to Proposition 8.2, physiformer isn't looking in the shape.

40:53.540 --> 40:55.880
It doesn't see a bunny, and it never saw a cube.

40:56.060 --> 40:58.360
It only sees a massive cluster of points.

40:58.480 --> 40:59.840
And it looks for the coherence.

40:59.840 --> 41:05.260
Yes, and it realizes, ah, this new cluster of points is obeying the exact same historical

41:05.260 --> 41:07.620
coherence relation as the points I trained on.

41:08.040 --> 41:09.640
The relative distances are constant.

41:09.940 --> 41:14.860
A cube is not a bunny visually, but to the AI, their rigidity is exactly the same mathematical

41:14.860 --> 41:15.340
language.

41:15.640 --> 41:17.460
The AI learned a coherence detector.

41:17.800 --> 41:21.620
As long as the hundreds of vertices of the bunny maintain constant relative distance over

41:21.620 --> 41:26.720
time, the AI just projects that entirely novel shape onto the admissible manifold and

41:26.720 --> 41:28.220
treats it exactly like a cube.

41:28.220 --> 41:33.380
It forces us to realize how differently AI perceives reality compared to humans.

41:33.980 --> 41:36.560
We are blinded by geometry and semantic labels.

41:37.180 --> 41:41.840
The AI is blind to shape, but possesses superhuman vision for coherence structure.

41:42.080 --> 41:43.320
That is wild!

41:43.640 --> 41:47.860
It looks past the skin of the object and reads the invariant mathematical skeleton underneath.

41:47.860 --> 41:53.020
Generalization in this new paradigm isn't about recognizing a new object.

41:53.020 --> 41:58.520
It is about recognizing the underlying coherent structure across wild geometric variations.

41:58.520 --> 42:02.960
The universe is just a massive swirling storm of points, and the ones that happen to dance

42:02.960 --> 42:05.600
together in a predictable pattern we call objects.

42:05.900 --> 42:07.000
That is staggering.

42:07.420 --> 42:08.680
It is a profound abstraction.

42:08.940 --> 42:11.780
And the beauty of this level of abstraction is that it scales.

42:12.820 --> 42:15.460
Which brings us to the final major concept of the paper.

42:15.960 --> 42:17.240
We need to zoom all the way out.

42:17.800 --> 42:22.520
Because Flyxion argues that this entire framework repairing broken trajectories onto an admissible

42:22.520 --> 42:27.160
manifold based on historical coherence doesn't just apply to rigid teapods and cubes.

42:27.160 --> 42:28.120
It's bigger than that.

42:28.600 --> 42:31.500
This mathematics is the blueprint for all world models.

42:31.880 --> 42:36.500
We hear the term world model thrown around a lot in Silicon Valley right now, usually meaning

42:36.500 --> 42:40.620
like an AI that can guess what happens next in a video.

42:41.080 --> 42:44.560
But Flyxion tightens this definition significantly.

42:45.200 --> 42:49.220
A world model is not just a video predictor, it is an admissibility engine.

42:49.320 --> 42:49.700
Exactly.

42:50.240 --> 42:53.040
Its job is not to play out a single deterministic tape.

42:53.040 --> 42:58.300
Its fundamental function is to construct admissible continuations of present states, strictly

42:58.300 --> 43:01.480
constrained by the rules of whatever domain it is operating in.

43:01.800 --> 43:05.640
So if the domain is a physics simulation, the constraints are the things we've been

43:05.640 --> 43:06.260
talking about.

43:06.360 --> 43:08.440
Rigidity, momentum, collision geometry.

43:09.160 --> 43:13.160
But this math maps perfectly onto domains that have nothing to do with physics.

43:13.280 --> 43:15.100
It maps onto large language models.

43:15.220 --> 43:15.600
It does.

43:15.960 --> 43:20.800
An LLM, like the one powering a chatbot, is fundamentally an admissibility engine for the

43:20.800 --> 43:21.940
domain of natural language.

43:22.280 --> 43:23.420
Think about the process.

43:23.880 --> 43:27.800
The prompt you type in, write a poem about a robot, is the witness.

43:28.120 --> 43:29.760
It is the partial initial condition.

43:30.020 --> 43:34.520
And the LLM doesn't have a single deterministic pre-written poem waiting for it.

43:34.600 --> 43:37.740
It isn't pulling the one true future text out of a database.

43:38.320 --> 43:38.640
No.

43:39.300 --> 43:43.800
The LLM samples from a massive manifold of admissible continuations.

43:44.380 --> 43:46.280
It explores the continuation entropy.

43:46.280 --> 43:51.220
It constructs a sequence of words that are constrained by the rules of grammar, the rules

43:51.220 --> 43:54.440
of semantics, and the contextual boundaries of your prompt.

43:54.780 --> 43:55.840
It repairs the blank space.

43:56.060 --> 43:58.880
It repairs the blank space into a coherent history of language.

43:59.680 --> 44:04.980
This exact same admissibility, math, applies to economic modeling, predicting how markets

44:04.980 --> 44:06.480
will react to a supply shock.

44:06.940 --> 44:10.520
It applies to robot planning, mapping out how to navigate a crowded room.

44:11.360 --> 44:15.600
Any domain where the future is constrained by rules can be modeled as an admissibility engine.

44:15.600 --> 44:21.060
To visualize how an admissibility engine navigates the future, the paper introduces one final

44:21.060 --> 44:25.180
mathematical concept, the optionality field, represented by the symbol omega.

44:25.780 --> 44:27.400
What is the optionality field measuring?

44:27.580 --> 44:29.660
Currently, models output a trajectory.

44:30.140 --> 44:33.740
But Flyxion argues a true-world model shouldn't just output a path.

44:33.880 --> 44:38.340
It should output a map of how open the future is at any given coordinate in space and time.

44:38.500 --> 44:40.260
Like a heat map of possibility.

44:40.440 --> 44:43.800
The optionality field measures how many admissible futures remain available.

44:43.800 --> 44:46.200
It's a topographic map of possibility.

44:46.480 --> 44:49.140
Okay, let me try to visualize this topographic map.

44:49.380 --> 44:50.800
Let's go back to our free-flight baseball.

44:51.240 --> 44:52.180
I throw the ball.

44:52.900 --> 44:56.680
While it's arguing through the empty air, its trajectory is locked by gravity.

44:57.180 --> 45:01.120
So the optionality field surrounding the ball is very tight, very small.

45:01.260 --> 45:02.440
The future is constrained.

45:02.660 --> 45:02.900
Right.

45:03.400 --> 45:05.740
The future is a narrow, flat plane.

45:06.140 --> 45:07.440
There aren't many branching paths.

45:07.640 --> 45:08.060
Correct.

45:08.060 --> 45:09.380
The constraints are dominating.

45:10.020 --> 45:11.780
But now, imagine a different scenario.

45:12.540 --> 45:15.860
Imagine two rigid bodies hurtling toward each other.

45:16.480 --> 45:18.580
Two meteorites in the vacuum of space.

45:18.800 --> 45:21.560
Or two cars skidding through a rainy intersection.

45:22.020 --> 45:23.480
And they narrowly miss each other.

45:23.840 --> 45:26.500
They pass within a fraction of a millimeter, but they don't touch.

45:26.660 --> 45:27.380
And near-miss.

45:27.640 --> 45:27.860
Right.

45:28.080 --> 45:31.880
At the exact mathematical moment of that near-miss, what happens to the optionality field?

45:32.140 --> 45:33.280
It spikes massively.

45:33.460 --> 45:35.660
It erupts into a mountain on our topographic map.

45:35.680 --> 45:36.420
Why does it spike?

45:36.420 --> 45:41.440
Because the post-near-miss trajectories are suddenly hypersensitive to microscopic, unobserved

45:41.440 --> 45:42.020
parameters.

45:42.720 --> 45:47.960
If those cars or meteorites had touched even slightly, if a single molecule of paint had

45:47.960 --> 45:53.420
scraped the resulting spin, the deflection, the massive transfer of kinetic energy, would

45:53.420 --> 45:56.140
have shattered the timeline into a wildly different future.

45:56.480 --> 46:00.940
The smallest change in the witness would create a completely divergent reality.

46:01.200 --> 46:01.540
Exactly.

46:01.760 --> 46:05.720
So right at the point of the near-miss, the universe of possibility balloons outward.

46:05.720 --> 46:10.780
The future is suddenly wide open, highly uncertain, full of chaotic, branching paths.

46:11.640 --> 46:16.040
And then, a millisecond later, once they pass each other safely and separate, the field

46:16.040 --> 46:16.860
collapses again.

46:16.960 --> 46:17.640
Back to normal.

46:17.760 --> 46:21.160
The mountain flattens back out into a predictable, constrained trajectory.

46:21.160 --> 46:26.980
The universe was suddenly violently wide open, and then collapsed back into a single, quiet

46:26.980 --> 46:27.480
line.

46:27.980 --> 46:29.900
I want to connect this back to you, the listener.

46:30.360 --> 46:33.360
Think about your own life in terms of this optionality field.

46:33.760 --> 46:35.980
Think about the moment where your personal field spiked.

46:36.320 --> 46:37.060
We've all had them.

46:37.260 --> 46:39.040
Maybe it was a literal near-miss.

46:39.600 --> 46:41.640
A time you were driving, someone swerved.

46:41.980 --> 46:43.520
Time seemed to slow to a crawl.

46:43.520 --> 46:48.320
And a thousand different tragic futures flashed before your eyes before you safely pulled

46:48.320 --> 46:48.700
the wheel.

46:49.200 --> 46:52.460
In that fraction of a second, your optionality field erupted.

46:52.980 --> 46:56.780
The universe of admissible futures was terrifyingly vast.

46:57.360 --> 46:58.000
And then it passed.

46:58.340 --> 46:59.560
Or maybe it wasn't physical.

46:59.780 --> 47:01.240
Maybe it was a split-second decision.

47:01.660 --> 47:06.240
Standing in an airport, choosing whether to say yes to a job offer in a new city or stay

47:06.240 --> 47:06.520
home.

47:06.520 --> 47:10.560
In that moment of decision, your optionality field spiked massively.

47:11.120 --> 47:17.080
A whole multiverse of branching, completely coherent, admissible lives opened up before

47:17.080 --> 47:17.300
you.

47:17.480 --> 47:18.200
And then you chose.

47:18.420 --> 47:21.880
And the moment you made the choice, the moment you bought the ticket, the field collapsed

47:21.880 --> 47:24.860
back down, and you were locked onto a single trajectory again.

47:25.140 --> 47:29.720
It is a profoundly human way to interpret the mathematics of trajectory prediction.

47:30.200 --> 47:34.480
What Flyxion is ultimately arguing is that successful prediction, whether for a bouncing

47:34.480 --> 47:40.640
block, a language model, or perhaps even a mind, is not the computation of a unique, destined

47:40.640 --> 47:42.620
truth from perfect specifications.

47:43.020 --> 47:44.440
It's about dealing with the mess.

47:44.780 --> 47:50.660
It is the construction of admissible continuations from messy, incomplete witnesses, coupled with

47:50.660 --> 47:55.060
a deep understanding of how tightly those witnesses constrain the chaos of the future.

47:55.520 --> 48:00.180
The goal is to report not just what will happen, but how constrained the future has become.

48:00.500 --> 48:04.160
Okay, let's take a deep breath and recap the massive intellectual genie we just went

48:04.160 --> 48:04.400
on.

48:04.780 --> 48:06.580
We started by killing Laplace's demon.

48:07.100 --> 48:11.940
We dismantled the myth of the complete state, realizing that we never have perfect information

48:11.940 --> 48:15.080
and that the gap in our knowledge isn't a blurry error.

48:15.560 --> 48:17.780
It is the map of physical possibility.

48:18.400 --> 48:21.260
From there, we shifted our entire ontology of time.

48:21.900 --> 48:27.000
We moved from frozen snapshots to histories before states, recognizing that the continuous

48:27.000 --> 48:29.580
trajectory is the fundamental unit of reality.

48:29.700 --> 48:31.480
Which changed how we compute everything.

48:31.480 --> 48:37.200
This allowed us to understand the admissibility compression principle, why AI can bypass impossible

48:37.200 --> 48:42.760
30,000 dimensional calculations, by simply learning the narrow geometric tracks of physically

48:42.760 --> 48:43.720
valid histories.

48:44.100 --> 48:47.240
And we fundamentally redefined diffusion models.

48:47.380 --> 48:49.260
They aren't generating images from static.

48:49.420 --> 48:51.380
They are iterative repair operators.

48:51.820 --> 48:57.360
They use temporal attention to pull the future and the past together, bending noisy, impossible

48:57.360 --> 49:00.700
timelines until they snap onto the manifold of reality.

49:00.700 --> 49:03.260
A completely new view of generation.

49:03.580 --> 49:08.400
We learned that our starting conditions are just witnesses, barely narrowing down the suspects

49:08.400 --> 49:11.980
of the future, measured by continuation entropy and the lambda functional.

49:12.280 --> 49:18.240
We face the uncomfortable truth that current AI models are trapped in Plato's cave, learning

49:18.240 --> 49:23.680
the kinematic shadows of motion rather than the causal mechanics of forces, requiring theoretical

49:23.680 --> 49:30.160
extensions like the RSVP field's capacity, transport, and constraints to truly understand the world.

49:30.160 --> 49:35.200
And we learned that to teach them we must break them structurally, abandoning Gaussian noise for

49:35.200 --> 49:37.260
admissibility-structured perturbations.

49:37.260 --> 49:42.000
And we shattered our perception of reality with the idea that objects themselves do not exist as

49:42.000 --> 49:47.520
primitive entities. They are emergent patterns of historical coherence. A rigid bunny and a rigid

49:47.520 --> 49:50.860
cube speak the exact same mathematical language to an AI.

49:50.860 --> 49:56.940
All of this culminating in the grand vision of world models as admissibility engines, navigating the

49:56.940 --> 50:00.460
sudden spikes and collapses of the optionality field of our universe.

50:00.460 --> 50:07.100
It is a dense, elegant, and structurally radical framework. It proves mathematically that our

50:07.100 --> 50:12.300
physical worlds are massively over-constrained and that prediction only works because coherent

50:12.300 --> 50:15.840
histories can be repaired from the fragments of partial witnesses.

50:15.840 --> 50:21.420
Which brings us to a final provocative thought for you to carry with you. We open this deep dive

50:21.420 --> 50:27.020
talking about the desire for clear, binary, perfect prediction in a messy world.

50:27.020 --> 50:31.900
Flyxion's paper shows us that artificial intelligence is mastering this world not by

50:31.900 --> 50:37.420
demanding perfect information, but by accepting the mess and iteratively repairing broken histories

50:37.420 --> 50:39.740
based on the underlying coherence of the universe.

50:39.740 --> 50:40.860
That's the key takeaway.

50:40.860 --> 50:46.780
But if physical worlds are just persistent, histories repaired from partial witnesses turn that lens inward.

50:46.780 --> 50:51.500
Look at how your own human memory works. Look at human consciousness itself.

50:51.500 --> 50:55.580
When you sit down and try to remember your past, or when you close your eyes and try to predict your

50:55.580 --> 50:59.500
tomorrow, are you accessing a perfect, complete state of your brain?

50:59.500 --> 51:00.860
You definitely aren't.

51:00.860 --> 51:07.580
Do you have perfect, frictionless information about your own life? Of course not. Your memories are fragmented.

51:07.580 --> 51:13.100
Your perception of the present is incredibly biased and incomplete. Perhaps your own brain is just a

51:13.100 --> 51:15.100
biological admissibility engine.

51:15.100 --> 51:19.900
That is a terrifying and beautiful thought. Perhaps your mind is constantly doing iterative

51:19.900 --> 51:25.420
repair on the messy, noisy, partial witness of your senses. You take your incomplete memories,

51:25.420 --> 51:30.380
your fragmented desires, and your brain iteratively bends them, rejecting the impossible,

51:30.380 --> 51:35.260
until it projects you forward onto a coherent manifold of reality. You aren't calculating your

51:35.260 --> 51:40.860
destined future step by step. You are constantly, every second of every day, repairing your timeline

51:40.860 --> 51:45.660
into an admissible continuation. Think about that the next time you try to predict your own future.

